An overview of the results is given in Fig. 1A (study 1) and B (study 2) and Table 4A, Table 4B
(study 4). All urine samples from studies 1–4 were negative for leptospires before challenge. Leptospires could be isolated from the kidneys of all control dogs and from the urine of 37.5% and 30% of the control dogs in studies 1 and 2, respectively. In contrast, none of the vaccinated dogs from studies 1 and 2 had any positive urine or kidney cultures at the time of euthanasia. The proportion of dogs with renal infection, characterized by the presence of leptospires in urine and/or kidneys, was significantly lower in the vaccinated dogs compared to the controls dogs in both studies (Table 5
).
